50|$|In 2013, a study {{conducted}} by Loas, Dimassi, Monetes, and Yon proposed that validity could also be assessed by comparing the CSS results of healthy first-degree relatives <b>of</b> individuals with <b>schizophrenia</b> to those without it. They recruited 27 first-degree relatives <b>of</b> individuals with <b>schizophrenia</b> and thirty first-degree relatives <b>of</b> individuals without <b>schizophrenia.</b> All participants were administered the French version of the CSS. The results indicate that the first-degree relatives <b>of</b> individuals with <b>schizophrenia</b> scored significantly higher on the CSS than did the first-degree relatives of typically developed individuals.|$|R
